WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.280 --> 00:00:06.170
R+L=J is a fan theory regarding George R.
R. Martin's Song of Ice and Fire, the basis

00:00:06.170 --> 00:00:10.349
of HBO's Game of Thrones. It's one of the
best-supported and most widely believed fan

00:00:10.349 --> 00:00:15.639
theories. The idea is that Jon Snow is not
the bastard son of Eddard Stark and an unknown

00:00:15.639 --> 00:00:20.580
woman, as Jon and most of Westeros believes,
but is actually the son of Ned's sister, Lyanna

00:00:20.580 --> 00:00:25.590
Stark, and Rhaegar Targaryen. So, for a bit
of context, Prince Rhaegar Targaryen was the

00:00:25.590 --> 00:00:30.630
son of the Mad King Aerys Targaryen, who was
overthrown in Robert Baratheon's Rebellion,

00:00:30.630 --> 00:00:36.170
the war that made Robert king. Lyanna is kind
of the Helen of Troy of Westeros because Robert's

00:00:36.170 --> 00:00:40.420
Rebellion started when Lyanna, who at the
time was betrothed to Robert, was abducted

00:00:40.420 --> 00:00:45.069
by or more likely ran away with Prince Rhaegar,
who was already married to Elia

00:00:45.069 --> 00:00:46.609
Martell. Rhaegar spent

00:00:46.609 --> 00:00:53.609
the start of the war in the Tower of Joy, in Dorne,
with Lyanna, before going off to battle, and to his doom, in the form of Robert's

00:00:53.609 --> 00:00:56.200
hammer. So after the war was over, Ned

00:00:56.280 --> 00:01:01.519
and six others headed to the Tower to find Lyanna, where they were confronted by three of the dead King's guard. When

00:01:01.519 --> 00:01:05.820
the fight was over, the two survivors, Ned
and his friend Howland Reed, went up the tower

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:10.490
to find Lyanna Stark "in a bed of blood".
There, Lyanna got Ned to make her a promise

00:01:10.490 --> 00:01:17.490
before she died. So R+L=J suggests that Lyanna's
"bed of blood" is one of childbirth, the baby

00:01:17.619 --> 00:01:22.299
is Rhaegar and Lyanna's, and that Ned's promise
to Lyanna is to pretend that the child is

00:01:22.299 --> 00:01:26.380
his in order to protect the child from Robert,
who would see the son of the Targaryen prince

00:01:26.380 --> 00:01:30.340
as a threat and likely have him killed, just
as he had Rhaegar's wife and other children

00:01:30.340 --> 00:01:35.259
killed. In any case, Ned then comes back from
the war with a baby, Jon, who until his death

00:01:35.259 --> 00:01:40.670
he raises as his own son in Winterfell.
So that's the theory. What's the evidence

00:01:40.670 --> 00:01:44.960
that makes it more plausible than the alternative,
that Jon really is Ned's bastard?

00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:49.880
Firstly, it seems very out-of-character for
Ned Stark, a painfully honourable person,

00:01:49.880 --> 00:01:54.119
to have fathered a bastard. In Ned's own words,
to have fathered Jon was to "dishonor ... [himself]

00:01:54.119 --> 00:01:59.200
and ... dishonor ... Catelyn, in the sight
of gods and men". Ned isn't like Robert, who

00:01:59.200 --> 00:02:04.039
would "swear undying love and forget them
before evenfall", Ned "[keeps] his vows".

00:02:04.039 --> 00:02:08.500
So right away it seems unlikely that Ned would
break his wedding vows to Catelyn by fathering

00:02:08.500 --> 00:02:12.319
Jon.
At one point Ned refers to Jon as his "blood",

00:02:12.319 --> 00:02:16.040
but he never calls him his son.
At one point, he internally lists his children,

00:02:16.040 --> 00:02:21.480
naming "Robb and Sansa and Arya and Bran
and Rickon". The very next line he mentions

00:02:21.480 --> 00:02:26.909
Jon, but not part of the list of his children.
Speaking of Arya – Jon is said to look like

00:02:26.909 --> 00:02:30.349
her, and Arya is said to look like Lyanna.
Anyway, so

00:02:30.349 --> 00:02:34.400
during a conversation with Robert about the
Rebellion, Ned thinks that "He [has] lived his

00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:38.569
lies for fourteen years".
What "lies" are Ned be referring to? Here's

00:02:38.569 --> 00:02:43.239
a hint – Jon is, at the start of the first
book, fourteen years old.

00:02:43.239 --> 00:02:50.239
So what all these hints amount to is that Jon is Ned's lie, a lie that "[haunts] him at night", but which he persists with, because

00:02:50.629 --> 00:02:55.340
"Some secrets are safer kept hidden. Some
secrets are too dangerous to share, even with

00:02:55.340 --> 00:02:59.739
those you love and trust"
It hurts Ned to lie like this, but he does

00:02:59.739 --> 00:03:04.260
it to keep his promise to his sister, to protect
his sister's son.

00:03:04.260 --> 00:03:07.640
One more thing about Ned – on multiple occassions, Ned opposes the killing

00:03:07.640 --> 00:03:11.709
of Targaryen children. When Robert orders
the assassination of Daenerys and her unborn

00:03:11.709 --> 00:03:16.000
child, Ned refuses, hurting his friendship
with Robert and endangering his honour and

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.900
life by disobeying the king. The other example
is his opposition to the killing of Rhaegar's

00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:24.310
wife and children at the Sack of King's Landing.
This refusal to kill

00:03:24.310 --> 00:03:28.280
children for the sake of their Targaryen
blood is mirrored by Ned's protection of Jon.

00:03:28.280 --> 00:03:30.540
To return briefly to the Tower of Joy, it

00:03:30.540 --> 00:03:35.069
seems very odd for three members of the Kingsguard
to be there with Lyanna Stark. Shouldn't they

00:03:35.069 --> 00:03:39.140
be protecting the siblings of the now-dead
Prince? A very good explanation for their

00:03:39.140 --> 00:03:44.640
presence is that they were guarding the heir
apparent, the son of the prince, Jon.

00:03:44.640 --> 00:03:48.069
So now to Essos, for a Biggie in terms of textual
evidence.

00:03:48.069 --> 00:03:52.349
While in House of the Undying, in Qarth, Daenerys
has a vision of "A blue flower [growing] from a

00:03:52.349 --> 00:03:55.989
chink in a wall of ice, and [filling] the air
with sweetness".

00:03:55.989 --> 00:04:01.180
Blue flowers, specifically blue winter roses,
are consistently associated with Lyanna Stark. At the Tourney

00:04:01.180 --> 00:04:06.019
of Harrenhal, Rhaegar selected Lyanna as the
“Queen of Love and Beauty” – over his wife – and presented

00:04:06.019 --> 00:04:10.799
her with a crown of blue winter roses. A storm
of blue rose petals feature in Ned's dream

00:04:10.799 --> 00:04:16.359
about Lyanna, and the statue of Lyanna in Winterfell
Crypt has a garland of blue winter roses.

00:04:16.359 --> 00:04:20.709
What this strongly suggests is that something
to do with Lyanna is at a "wall of ice". That

00:04:20.709 --> 00:04:25.720
something is very probably Jon on the Wall.
So given all these hints, it seems

00:04:25.720 --> 00:04:31.750
very likely that Jon Snow is the son of Rhaegar
Targaryen and Lyanna Stark. But what are

00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:36.560
the implications of R+L=J?
It's been suggested that being both a Stark

00:04:36.560 --> 00:04:42.080
and a Targaryen makes Jon the Song of Ice
and Fire personified. What this actually means,

00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:46.860
exactly, is unclear but it does seem to suggest
that Jon is very important, perhaps he's the

00:04:46.860 --> 00:04:51.710
Prince that was Promised, or Azor Ahai, or
one of the three heads of the dragon, or any

00:04:51.710 --> 00:04:55.840
of the other various prophecised figures.
In any case, Stark blood is associated with

00:04:55.840 --> 00:05:00.220
powers like warging, and Targaryen blood is
associated with an affinity with dragons and

00:05:00.220 --> 00:05:05.069
fire. Jon having both would possibly make
him capable of some pretty impressive stuff.

00:05:05.069 --> 00:05:09.780
A more concrete implication is that, if Jon
is the son of Prince Rhaegar, he has a claim

00:05:09.780 --> 00:05:14.460
on the Iron Throne – more so than Dany, actually.
That's assuming, though, that Rhaegar and

00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:17.810
Lyanna were secretly wedded, which could have
happened despite Rhaegar's existing marriage

00:05:17.810 --> 00:05:22.360
to Elia – polygamy is a bit of a thing with
Targaryens – but if they weren't married,

00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:25.770
Jon would still be considered a bastard, and
an illegitimate contender for the throne,

00:05:25.770 --> 00:05:30.330
though he could possibly be legitimised. Jon's
vows with the Night's Watch are another complication.

00:05:30.330 --> 00:05:34.380
He's sworn an oath to "hold no lands", to
"wear no crown" – so surely he can't be king.

00:05:34.380 --> 00:05:38.380
But even if he could overcome that barrier,
would anyone believe his claim to the throne?

00:05:38.380 --> 00:05:44.490
How could he prove his parentage? And besides, it seems doubtful that Jon would even want the Throne.
Powers and thrones aside, finding out his

00:05:44.490 --> 00:05:48.759
true parentage would be very significant for Jon
personally. He's always struggled with rejection

00:05:48.759 --> 00:05:53.650
from Cat, alienation from being a bastard,
and the difficulty of not knowing his mother.

00:05:53.650 --> 00:05:58.590
Finding out his true parentage would undoubtedly
be a big deal for him, if not for all of Westeros.

00:05:58.590 --> 00:06:03.110
So that's R+L=J – the main evidence, and some
of the possible implications. Let me know

00:06:03.110 --> 00:06:06.190
in the comments what you think of the theory,
and whether you'd like to see more videos

00:06:06.190 --> 00:06:10.889
on A Song of Ice and Fire fan theories – some
of which are pretty crazy and awesome.

00:06:10.889 --> 00:06:13.560
If you're interested in A Song of Ice and
Fire fan theories and discussion, you

00:06:13.560 --> 00:06:17.680
might like to check out westeros.org, the
wiki, and the subreddit.

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:18.680
That's all from me.
Thanks for watching this video.

